Sin cos diiungent, hoc erunt inferiores, quod in oratore perfecto inest illorum omnis scientia, in philosophorum autem cognitione non continuo inest eloquentia; quae quamvis contemnatur ab eis, necesse est tamen aliquem cumulum illorum artibus adferre videatur.

As to the relative values, however, ot* philosophy and rhetoric, further than that wisdom without eloquence is preferable to elo- quence without wisdom, Augustine does not concern himself. Yet he makes a like assumption, in the case of the training of the ecclesi- astical orator, as that made by the teachers of rhetoric, that although there can be no need in theological investigations for error to be made to appear superior to nuth, yet truth when wielded by a worthy and conscientious defender, can be made to do quick and effective service if adorned by the noble art of rhetoric.
